{{Unreferenced section|date=November 2018}}
'''Open Spring Legends''' (開湯伝説, Kaitō Densetsu) are traditional tales and legends about the origins of the discovery of {{ill|onsen|ja|温泉}}. These are oral traditions and differ from historical fact (explained below).

== Overview ==
*
* '''White Foxes:''' {{ill|Yuda Onsen|ja|湯田温泉}}
* '''White Wolves:''' {{ill|Misasa Onsen|ja|三朝温泉}}
* '''Deer:''' {{ill|Yamaga Onsen|ja|山鹿温泉}}, {{ill|Kakeyu Onsen|ja|鹿教湯温泉}}
* '''Monkeys:''' {{ill|Tawarayama Onsen|ja|俵山温泉}}
* '''Snakes:''' {{ill|Oigami Onsen|ja|老神温泉}}

In reality, villagers, hunters, or woodsmen likely discovered the springs after observing animals bathing in them. The association with animals was likely used to make the story more relatable and convincing.

== References ==
* Noguchi, Fuyuhito. *Comprehensive Encyclopedia of Hot Springs Nationwide* (Travel Yomiuri Publishing, 1997), pp. 706–710.

== Related Topics ==
* {{ill|Onsen Shrine|ja|温泉神社}}
